<DOC><DOCNO> AP890131-0187 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1831EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-31 0354</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0361</SECOND><HEAD>Cold And Warm Weather Clash</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Record Highs</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Severe cold, high wind and blowing and drifting snow moved intothe north-central part of the nation Tuesday, while southerlybreezes from the Gulf of Mexico spread unseasonable warmth acrossthe central part of the nation.   At least 39 cities reported record high temperatures for thedate, from Colorado to Ohio and from Fort Worth, Texas, to St.Cloud, Minn.   But elsewhere, a blizzard warning was posted through the nightfor the eastern slopes of the Rockies in Montana, where East Glacierhad received 6 inches of snow by mid-afternoon and wind gusting upto 45 mph caused blowing and drifting snow and create very low windchill factors.   Storm warnings and watches also were posted for the rest ofMontana, northern Idaho, Wyoming, northern Colorado, northeasternNorth Dakota and northwestern Minnesota.   Elsewhere, snow fell over parts of the Northwest, including theCascade Mountains of Washington state and the mountains of Oregon,and a winter storm watch was posted for northwestern Oregon.   A few showers were scattered across New York state and Vermont.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 20degrees below zero at Cut Bank, Mont., to 82 at Fort Myers andNaples, Fla. Tuesday morning's low for the Lower 48 states was 19degrees below zero at Gunnison, Colo.   For Wednesday, snow was forecast over the mountains of thePacific Northwest through the northern high Plains to UpperMichigan, accompanied by strong, gusty wind over the northernPlains. Scattered showers were forecast from the central PacificCoast through the mid Mississippi Valley to New England.   Highs remaining below freezing were predicted from the centralRockies through Nebraska and the Dakotas to Upper Michigan,including highs remaining below zero across Montana and NorthDakota; above 50 from the southern and central coast of Californiathrough the southern half of the Plains to the Atlantic Coast, asfar north as southern New England; and in the 70s and lower 80s overmuch of the area from the southern Plains to the southern AtlanticCoast.</TEXT></DOC>